Ok, I give up.  What's an estoppel letter?
Fred Mitro@ECT
04/24/2001 11:11 AM
Given the challenges that Carlos and I are currently encountering while 
trying to obtain an estoppel letter from our Illinois landowner (Bob 
Konicek), I believe that it makes sense on all our future land option 
agreements to include language obligating the Seller to provide such letters 
at our request.  This language could be easily included in the cooperation 
section of the agreement and would likely go unnoticed or unchallenged by the 
Seller.  It would simplify the site monetization process and avoid the Seller 
being able to extract value from us in exchange for providing such a letter.

Fred

Sounds good to me, although we are likely to find different purchasers want 
other stuff as well.  Kinda like on the turbine stuff - each counterparty has 
wanted something different.

ckm

A letter whereby a party agrees that in the event of a change of control of 
its counterparty, it will not use such change of control event as a basis for 
challenging the enforceability of the agreement that it has with the 
counterparty.  At least in our context this is what Fred means by estoppel 
letter.  He has a very good point that we should incorporate this concept 
into our further assurances clause in our option agreements.

Carlos Sole'
Senior Counsel
(713) 345-8191 (phone)
713 646-3393 (fax)

